The stereotyped‘character of the introductory phrase with de is shown here by its lack of influence upon the construction of the rest of the sentence—hypomne- matis: the dative and ablative plural of Greek nouns in -ma ends sometimes in -ibus‚ sometimes in -is‚ with a decided preference in classical Latin for the heteroclite ending -is‚ as though the noun were a feminine noun of the first declension or a neuter of the second.— Anterum ε the tabella- rius.
